Right-wing populists win in Austria with 29 percent
The significant weakening of the two parties in the previous big coalition and the significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties were brought by the early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday, according to the first preliminary results.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of the current president, Wilhelm Molterer, was seriously shaken, suffered strong losses.
On the other hand, the President of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), Jörg Haider, is preparing for a victorious return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the most powerful party in the country remains the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) with 29.8 percent of the votes, but lost 5.5 percent of the votes compared to the last election in 2006.
Even worse was the situation for the ÖVP, which lost almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
These are the worst results ever achieved by both major parties in the post-war history of Austria, and especially in the People’s Party, which led to early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
At the start of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People’s Party had a significant advantage over the SPÖ, according to polls.
Voters, however, were apparently punished for letting the government fail.
In the early reactions to the results, there were speculations about the possible resignation of party chairman Wilhelm Molterer and current deputy chancellor.
Observers expect this to take place at the extraordinary meeting of the party’s leadership on Monday.
This development would likely facilitate the increasingly likely exit from the election result, i.e. the renewal of the large coalition of SPÖ and ÖVP.
Given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties – the Austrian Freedom Party (FPÖ) previously received 18 percent of the votes and the BZÖ received eleven percent of the votes – however, the Social Democrats expressed their fears of a recurrence of the year 1999 when the People’s Party agreed to joint governance with the populists (the FPÖ was still united at the time, replacing it with the BZÖ in 2005), which even prompted sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already stated that he is willing to cooperate with any party, and I assume he can return to Vienna in national politics, obviously expects this solution.
The Greens also entered parliament, but lost some popularity and fell from third to fifth among the Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties surpassed the four-percent threshold and did not enter parliament.
