Turkey's Expanding Diplomatic Horizons
Long before Turkey intended to join the European Union, European powers were burning with the desire to penetrate deep into the Turkish backland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, just 20 steps from the European border, stands one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial quest.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least the books write that.
The building surrounds the ends of the perrons, with one tower at each front corner, and looks like some German countryside town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slightly shattered.
However, when you look at the inside of the bulldozer, it is obvious how large-scale the business had this western gate.
The station was opened by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the “later future” of conquests, sought to realize its ambitions of occupying the Middle East using this railway from Damascus through Baghdad to today’s Saudi Arabia.
German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and Arab partisans.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
The Hyderpasha station was no better.
In 1917, an ammunition train exploded and destroyed the beautifully designed roof of the building.
According to Turkish sources, there was an act of sabotage.
Since then, it has slowly collapsed and has gone well beyond history.
At the same time, today, as a railway gateway to Anatolia and the entire Eastern region – at least in a symbolic sense – it serves as Turkey’s expanding diplomatic horizon.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has developed a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The new policy is marked by commitment.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian groups Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq, with Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to measure the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the AKP’s leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, after about ten and a half hours of darkness, which at the time gave me the rhythm of the famous documentary about the old world, The Night Mail - I arrived in the Turkish capital.
However, the AKP with well-known Islamic roots represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This has caused some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern building made of stone and steel, specially designed for this purpose - which stands in a developing suburban neighborhood, between semi-finished shopping centers and cafes. In the latter, dressed middle managers - both men and women - meet to do business early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have been a right-to-middle-minded politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a dress, a tie, and I’m sure he even had a Blackberry with him.
"The party's foreign policy goal is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War has disrupted the order,” he said.
Turkey is isolated.
He had to turn east and west at the same time.
He could not choose between the two.
It had to open in both directions.
"But is it possible that he will be forced to vote sooner or later?" I asked.
“Turkey never wanted to face a choice.”
He then emphasized what almost everyone I spoke with repeated almost automatically: Turkey’s relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the countries surrounding the Black Sea benefit Europe and the United States as well as Turkey itself.
As if they wanted to convey the message that, in a translated sense, along with Turkey, the whole of Europe can reach Asia and the Middle East on those railways that go east.
When I was again at the station of Hydarpasha, after another mostly awake night, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conura, the two German gentlemen who watched the reconstruction of this magnificent building 100 years ago.
They would be surprised to learn that Europe’s Middle Eastern ambitions are now largely in Turkey’s hands.
And as I waited in the harbour for the ferry to take you back through the Bosphorus, I remembered that Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe" at that time.
At the time, at least there was no question which continent would claim to this exciting country.
