The “Collision Vehicle”
For the development of accident-prevention technologies, Nissan this time drew inspiration from nature, precisely from the world of bees, for its new invention.
A Japanese company has developed a robot that can avoid accidents by imitating bees.
The Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C may be the first step in the development of collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technology Center in collaboration with Tokyo University’s Advanced Science and Technology Research Center in Japan have built this small robot.
Kazuhhiro Doi, Head of Technology Public Relations and Research & Development, defines the BR23C as a further extension of Nissan’s four-layer safety cover.
The robot increases the collision avoidance capability of the company’s products.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety cover.
However, much more important than this is the role of the complex eye of the uterus, with which it can see at angles of more than 300 degrees in all directions.
To copy the function of the complex eye, the engineers designed a so-called Laser Range Finder.
In front of the BR23C, the instrument identifies obstacles within a 180-degree range of up to 2 meters, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is immediately converted into an operation to avoid a collision.
As soon as the obstacle is detected, the small robot imitates the movements of the uterus and immediately changes direction by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle to avoid collision.
The system is most distinguished from the currently available instruments by the fact that in this case the avoidance maneuver takes place completely automatically.
Otherwise, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the circumventing maneuver cannot be directed up or down, nor can it be diagonal, it can only move in two dimensions and only in the direction of the reversibility of the wheels, that is, not in an infinite direction and way as is the case with bees.
That’s why Nissan used a rotation function in the robot in addition to acceleration and slowing down to avoid collisions.
“This structure only needs to process the data every few seconds and respond to it.
There is no need for data storage or intuitive logic based on previous manoeuvres, so it can work without interruption with just a few dozen KB of memory.
It may sound surprising, but it’s not really gigabytes, but we’re not even talking about megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of immediate collision prevention technology, which Nissan estimates could be used in mass-production vehicles within ten years.
The robot is powered by lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, additional applications could include integrating the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system to get the car to its final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
