Morgan Stanley approved a new status last week, allowing it to diversify its operations while being under the control of the Federal Reserve.
The agreement with MUFG reaffirms that the current financial crisis requires even greater caution from Wall Street-listed companies.
The terms announced on Monday indicate that the agreement has been amended in recent days: on Monday, Morgan only announced that it would sell 20% of its shares to the Japanese company for approximately $8.5 billion.
“A week ago, we thought the shares would be made entirely from shareholders,” said Toshihide Mizuno, MUFG’s chief executive officer in Tokyo.
"But given the current market and economic situation, we wanted to minimize and avoid potential risks."
