Declaration by Rafael Correa on Monday, Quito
The reconstruction of the republic in the spirit of 21st century socialism.
This is a joint plan by Hugo Chávez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Correa of Ecuador.
Following the pattern of his fellow presidents and friends, Correa explained his ideas on the new constitution on Sunday.
He successfully fulfilled his mission, with 64% of voters voting in favour in the referendum according to the official results, which referred to 80% of the votes.
According to the report, 28% of the population voted no, 7% of the votes were invalid, while 0.7% were left unfilled by voters.
The bill needed 50% + 1 vote to be adopted.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the polling stations and a counting by a non-governmental organization both showed the overwhelming superiority of the “yes” votes by 63% and 70% respectively.
Rafael Correa spoke about the victory of his draft constitution on Sunday night.
"The constitution has won an overwhelming victory," he said, thanking the Ecuadorians in Guayaquil, a governor's seat 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As well as the well-known, Rafael Correa was congratulated by Chavez, Morales and Chilean President Michelle Bachelet.
According to a report from the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, the vote took place in a calm atmosphere. Its main theme was a 444-point text that summarized the principles of "new socialism" defended by the president.
The proposed constitution puts state power at the service of the economy, reserving the state the right to "planning development" for a country that basically lives on oil mining by foreign companies and currency sent by expatriates.
The Correa Constitution, elected in 2006, also reinforces the power of the head of state, who can hold up to two consecutive terms and has the power to dissolve the parliament.
Correa has already announced that he will take advantage of this opportunity and will compete again for the presidency in February 2009.
The president has already begun introducing it in his country, which has 13.9 million inhabitants and half of the population lives below the minimum.
Finally, the Constitution prohibits the presence of foreign troops in the country. This could end the Quito and Washington agreement on the use of the Ecuadorian facility as a base for U.S. anti-drug measures.
Thirteen hostages released in Chad
Egyptian captors took 11 tourists and eight accompanies hostage for 10 days.
The hostages are now in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts were detained in the desert for ten days, from where they were transported uninjured to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
The hostages were released in the morning by an Egyptian commander in Chad.
Apparently in good condition, they arrived by plane at about half four in the afternoon at the Al-Maza military base, which is directly connected to Cairo International Airport.
The hostages were forbidden from stating to the press and were immediately taken to a hospital in Maadi, a suburban residential district of Cairo, where they were examined.
The hostages are “healthy” and “no ransom paid” to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said at the airport.
The hostages were captured on September 19 at the foot of the Ouanat mountain on the border of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, where they took part in off-road safari, and were then carried from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown hostages.
The group included 11 tourists (five Italian men, five German men and one Romanian woman) and eight Egyptians: two tour guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the travel agency Aegyptous, which organized the safari.
According to an Egyptian security official, a 30-member Special Command arrived on two helicopters and hit the hostages just before dawn.
"There was a fight of fire between the troops, half of the kidnappers were killed and the rest fled," the leader said.
He also said that a total of 150 special forces were sent from the Egyptian Lightning Brigade to Sudan, where they were supplemented with German and Italian commanders.
Italian diplomatic chief Franco Frattini, who is currently in Belgrade, stressed the role of secret agents and Italian special operations groups.
"We must acknowledge that this result could not have been achieved without the professional and effective intervention of our intelligence personnel and action groups," he said.
He also denied paying a ransom for the hostages.
The previous day, the Sudanese army announced that during a patrol, a off-road vehicle in which the kidnappers were travelling was arrested, six of them were killed (including the Chadi leader), and two were arrested.
The army said the hostages were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA-U), which the group immediately denied.
