Benelux Governments Nationalise Part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux countries will help with partial nationalization of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortison, which was the first European bank in trouble due to the impact of the US credit market crisis: the three countries will support the financial and insurance institution with interests in Hungary with a total of €11.2 billion.
The Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments discussed the issue at the highest level at the end of the week, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commission's competition chief.
Fortis is the first major crisis in the euro area in the context of a global financial market crisis that has been on the rise for more than a year, so decisions about the bank can therefore be regarded as precedent in some respects.
According to the decision, the three states will buy half (49 percent) of the bank’s existing assets.
The bank will surely sell some of its interests, including, above all, the activities it purchased from ABN Amro in the Netherlands last year, mostly insurance.
Fortis shares began to fall sharply last week, and in the second half of the week, the institute was already experiencing serious crisis phenomena.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to be allowed to go bankrupt.
The company’s securities dropped about 12 percent on Friday to a 14-year low.
Since January, the share value has fallen by more than two-thirds.
At current stock prices, the group’s total market capital is around €14 billion, but the company’s directors say this is unrealistic.
The company’s management blamed overseas market uncertainties over the adoption of the $700 billion U.S. package for the fall in Fortis shares.
On Monday, the prices increased slightly.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the new CEO of the bank.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but no one has made a substantial offer so far.
The Belgian government has already indicated that investors do not have to worry about losing their money.
There has been no panic among the bank’s clients so far, and the branches have not been attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has an independent branch and has also acquired leasing companies.
Race in the Chicken
In America, life and health insurance companies often refuse to sign an insurance contract with a applicant based on people’s drug purchase data.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that requires the use of prescription data in all cases with the consent of the person concerned.
This must be done independently, otherwise we’ll give the chicken to the fox,” said Richard Dicket, the developer of the prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the amount due in the event of damages dependent on the health condition of the applicant, and if they consider the risk too high, they do not contract insurance with him.
In the past, the person was sent for medical examination, and the contract was concluded only with the knowledge of the outcome of the examination.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: the pharmacy can easily obtain from the customer’s identification number what medicines the person has purchased in the last year and a half, and from this the program itself concludes what illness he suffers and what his health status is.
For example, if you regularly take high doses of cholesterol-lowering medication, it indicates that you have practically uncontrollably high blood fat levels, which immediately puts you in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which also define a risk multiplier, so the insurer has little to do outside of paperwork, although small difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include that some drugs can be used for multiple purposes, for example, some compounds can be used against migraines or heat waves, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter is considered to be a significant risk-increasing factor for business insurers, the former is not.
Special companies have been established to collect and process the data, and they ask for the consent of the patient before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies.
They are now obliged to do so by the authorities, although they have not been punished for their failure so far.
Some companies have recently processed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to drug consumption data to provide an even more accurate picture of patients’ health.
More and more companies have access to data, and it is becoming increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is a separate Health Data Protection Act, but it only covers healthcare providers and insurance companies.
There is a bill before Congress that gives authorities control over companies that specialize in reporting.
Dick Richard realizes that this is not enough: therefore he has improved his program, which would require the express consent of the data subject to the transmission of the data.
Another issue is that the person concerned can hardly refuse to consent, otherwise the insurers will not conclude a contract with him.
Thus, chickens are somewhat referred to as the kindness of the fox.
Global menu in Marseille
Trade between the EU and India doubles
As the European Union and India are each other’s leading trading partners, this theme dominated the agenda of the Ninth Summit, along with other, mostly global issues.
There will also be a French-India summit on nuclear cooperation.
While the European Union recognizes that India is an emerging democratic power that should have a greater voice in international affairs, member states have not yet reached a common denominator to support New Delhi’s permanent membership in the UN Security Council.
This issue was not addressed at the Ninth Summit in Marseille yesterday.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, European Commission President José Manuel Barroso and High Representative Javier Solana have welcomed India’s Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they have agreed to double trade in five years to more than 100 billion euros.
Given that trade increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not an overly ambitious goal.
In the wake of this, 26 bilateral civil aviation agreements with India have been agreed in a legal sense, meaning that air traffic could also be operated in the future.
India wants to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to accelerate the negotiations.
The goal is to balance that while the EU is India’s top trading partner, New Delhi is only ranked ninth among EU partners.
The summit focused on global issues.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, as well as terrorism, were condemned in all its forms by both sides and called for the convening of a UN conference.
They also called for the end of the Doha trade round, although both have much to do with the previous failure.
The EU has reaffirmed its commitment to its energy and climate agenda to reduce emissions by at least 20 percent by 2020.
India has also agreed to reach a global agreement at the upcoming climate conference to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 percent by 2050.
They also sought to prevent rising food prices and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
The Prime Minister of India is heading to the French capital for a bilateral meeting on the peaceful use of nuclear energy.
France has agreed to invest 20 billion euros in the construction of nuclear reactors in India.
According to news agencies, the deal will last for 15 years.
More than 300 Italian book publishers in Frankfurt
Italian publishers are strongly represented at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than three hundred Italian publishers will attend the most important international copyright meeting, the 60th Buchmesse.
This year’s Frankfurt International Book Fair will be attended by 7,000 exhibitors from 101 countries, with an area of 171,790 square meters and more than 403,000 books.
At the opening ceremony of the Italian Pavilion, the Italian government will be represented by Francesco Maria Giro, Deputy Secretary of State of the Ministry of Cultural Property and Activities: Italy will occupy an exhibition area of 264 square meters through the establishment of a single Italia Point.
