Billionaire Steve Fossett missing a year ago
Billionaire Steve Fossett's plane disappeared over the Nevada desert on September 3, 2007.
The debris was found on a 3,000-foot plateau near Mammoth Lakes in the Sierra Nevada mountains on the border of California and Nevada.
No human remains were found inside the plane.
John Anderson, Sheriff of Madera County, dissipated any remaining doubts: "After finding the location of the plane, we sent a team and now we can be sure it was the aircraft on which Steve Fossett flew on the day of his disappearance," he said at a news conference.
The sheriff also confirmed that no human remains were found either in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was declared dead in February.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Agency (NTSB) said hours after the debris was discovered, an investigation committee was called upon to identify the aircraft and determine that it was the Bellanca 8kcab that disappeared on September 3, 2007, the day Fossett took off on a three-hour flight from Yerington, Nevada.
Yesterday, also in California, not far from the Nevada border, a couple found some of Fossett’s personal belongings near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
Two Fosset cards issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Inspectorate, some cash and a sweater.
The search for Fossett was discontinued a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire set up a number of summits through which he entered into history.
In 2002, on a sixth attempt, he managed to fly around the Earth with a balloon for the first time: two weeks of solitary flight.
Three years later, he flew around the earth without landing.
Among his many records is his flight over the Andes at an altitude of 15,445 meters with a second pilot.
